WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.559
Thank you. All right. So my name is Jesse Sadler. I am a historian. I teach at Loyola

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:25.920
Marymount University. And so even though I am talking about vectors today, what I normally

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:32.799
do, and just quickly, the slides are online and I'll have a link at the end, but what

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:40.480
I normally do is I study history. I am a historian. I'm interested in merchant networks and merchant

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:50.160
families in the 16th and 17th century. And I'm particularly interested in inheritance

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:57.639
and what inheritance shows about how people interacted with each other and how families

00:00:57.639 --> 00:01:08.239
interacted with each other. And so that leads me to doing math, specifically in terms of

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:14.199
doing math with non-decimal currencies. So these are currencies like here, this is Flemish

00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:20.440
pounds, but basically currencies that are in pounds, shillings, and pence. And this

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:29.639
is a problem because we don't learn how to do non-decimal arithmetic anymore. And computers

00:01:29.639 --> 00:01:37.120
are obviously based on decimal arithmetic. And so you can't just plug these numbers into

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:43.879
a computer and do an analysis on them. It doesn't really work that way, unfortunately.

00:01:43.879 --> 00:01:50.839
So what exactly is the problem space? The problem space is that with non-decimal currencies,

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:58.080
you have to do something called compound unit arithmetic. So you have to add up the separate

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:06.239
columns and then divide by the base of that column. And then you can get your answer.

00:02:06.239 --> 00:02:12.399
So in other words, we have a number of different problems here. We have three separate units

00:02:12.399 --> 00:02:21.199
that make up one value. Those units do not have decimal bases. So therefore, we need

00:02:21.199 --> 00:02:28.559
to use this compound unit arithmetic. And finally, to make things even worse, the units

00:02:28.559 --> 00:02:39.559
can differ. So the normal most used units in historical currencies is to have 20 shillings

00:02:39.559 --> 00:02:46.919
in a pound and 12 pence in a shilling, but they could change. So you guys didn't know

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:52.679
you were getting so much history today. JJ, in the keynote, already talked about history

00:02:52.679 --> 00:03:03.479
of corporations. This is what he's talking about. I'll have some ideas about corporations.

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:11.279
So there's a problem, and you can't just plug this in. However, programming languages like

00:03:11.279 --> 00:03:21.759
R are very flexible. And so you can use them to do this essentially compound arithmetic

00:03:21.759 --> 00:03:29.679
yourself. So what we want to do in a situation like this is we want to take these totals,

00:03:29.679 --> 00:03:39.559
which are just added up, and then normalize them, do the compound unit arithmetic in order

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:48.679
to get the answer that we want. And so you can make a what I'm calling here a normalized

00:03:48.679 --> 00:03:55.720
function, which basically takes a vector of length 3, the amount of units that we have,

00:03:55.720 --> 00:04:04.479
and then normalizes them using a remainder division essentially, and then brings them

00:04:04.479 --> 00:04:13.720
all together. OK, so this is great. We have a normalized function. We're ready to go.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:22.959
We've got something. We can even create an S3 class. And S3 classes, who here has built

00:04:22.959 --> 00:04:28.160
their own S3 class before? All right, a number of you, right? S3 classes are great because

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:36.320
they're really easy to make, right? I just built an S3 class, right? The key here is

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:45.040
the structure part, right? And so this is a class that has a value into it, x. And then

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:53.760
it has, I call the class LSD, which is the Latin terminology for pounds, shillings, and

00:04:53.760 --> 00:05:04.720
pence. And then I've added a basis attribute so that we can know what the basis of the

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:10.959
shillings and pence units are. All right? And so I can just do this, and I can create

00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:16.880
something. And it doesn't have a nice printing method or anything right now, but I've created

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:24.359
an S3 class. OK, so great. I've created an S3 class. Now I'm going to sit down. I'm going

00:05:24.359 --> 00:05:30.040
to figure out what am I going to do with this? What else do I need to do? Well, right now,

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:35.839
I can only have one value at a time. So maybe I need to have multiple values, so I should

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:42.160
use a list or something. And then I need to change the normalization method. OK, no problem.

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:52.559
All right, so what else do I need to do? OK, at this point, it gets really confusing

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:58.760
because you have to implement all these methods. And it's not really clear how exactly you're

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:03.799
going to do them, and what methods you have to implement, and why you need to do them,

00:06:03.799 --> 00:06:09.519
and so on. And so basically, I went through this, and I implemented some methods and some

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:15.880
I didn't. And then I talked to Hadley Wickham, and he said, no, what you should do is that

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:27.559
you should use vectors. And so vectors is a package that gives you a path to implementing

00:06:27.559 --> 00:06:35.160
all of those different methods, to actually creating your own S3 class without having

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:41.559
to know everything there is to know about the different S3 classes.

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:51.559
So the goals of the vectors package are fairly simple in some ways, but very deep. It's about

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:57.239
type stability and size stability, and Hadley talked about this at the last RStudio conference.

00:06:57.239 --> 00:07:04.200
But I am going to focus on this last aspect of building S3 classes.

00:07:04.239 --> 00:07:10.079
So what do you get by using this vectors package? Well, as I said before, you get a clear path.

00:07:10.079 --> 00:07:15.359
But you also get consistency with base R. It's just an S3 class, and so there's no reason

00:07:15.359 --> 00:07:21.760
why your users would need to know that it's based on vectors. And then finally, it is

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:27.040
integrated and continuing to be integrated into the tidyverse.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:36.079
Okay, so what I want to do in this talk, and for the rest of the talk, basically, is talk

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:43.480
about why you might want to create your own S3 class through this example of non-decimal

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:50.079
currencies, why you should use vectors, and to point you to some things of how you can

00:07:50.079 --> 00:08:00.200
do it. And I don't have enough time to go through and do all of a tutorial on this and

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:07.399
show all the different steps. And so what I've done is I've created a package that I'm

00:08:07.399 --> 00:08:13.440
calling debvectors, which is a simplified version of the package where I've done more

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:20.959
of this in DebKeeper, and you see the URLs there. And what the debvectors package is,

00:08:20.959 --> 00:08:28.399
is it provides a tutorial of a step-by-step way to get through this, and I will go through

00:08:28.399 --> 00:08:37.000
some of these steps now. And so just as an aside, the image that you see there is a

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:41.960
trademark of an individual who would use that, so again, more history stuff.

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:52.159
Okay, so there's basically six different steps to creating a S3 class with vectors. Again,

00:08:52.159 --> 00:08:56.280
I'm not going to go through all these. I'm going to concentrate on the first half,

00:08:56.280 --> 00:09:03.960
the first three, and I won't go into the last three, but I will talk about them. You'll see

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:11.919
how they are when they're implemented. And if you're creating a class that's based on double

00:09:11.919 --> 00:09:17.239
vectors, you only have to do four of these, two of these steps you get for free. And so just to

00:09:17.239 --> 00:09:23.919
give you an idea, so debvectors is a package, and it's tested, and it has everything, but the way

00:09:23.919 --> 00:09:32.280
that the scripts are organized is to follow this, and then within the scripts, there's a lot of

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:37.080
different comments on how to do these things. So I definitely recommend that you go and look at

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:44.320
this that's on GitHub, and you see the URL there. Okay, so let's go through some of these choices

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:51.919
that I made with debkeeper slash debvectors. And so just as a reminder, right, to go back to our

00:09:51.919 --> 00:09:59.320
problem space, we have to deal with these issues of compound unit arithmetic, of representing a

00:09:59.359 --> 00:10:08.239
single value with three different numbers. So in designing this, I thought about different things.

00:10:08.239 --> 00:10:13.760
So one, I didn't want to just decimalize everything. I wanted to maintain the structure

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:19.919
of the numbers. I wanted to keep track of the bases of the shillings and pence because they

00:10:19.919 --> 00:10:28.840
could differ, and I wanted to make sure that if two values had different bases that they

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:36.400
couldn't be combined in any way. But at the same time, I did want to create a decimalized class

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:44.719
that I could use as a fallback, and this would have the same basic attributes of a bases attribute

00:10:44.719 --> 00:10:51.799
that you could follow what the different bases of the pounds and shillings are, but in addition,

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:59.359
it would have an attribute on the unit. So it would be a decimalized unit of the pounds unit,

00:10:59.359 --> 00:11:06.679
or the shillings unit, or the pence unit, right? And different units can come together because they

00:11:06.679 --> 00:11:13.960
can be the same currency, but there needs to be a way in which that's done. And so I'm calling

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:21.760
these classes DebLSD. Deb is short for Double Entry Bookkeeping, which is where you find all

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:29.679
these different values, and then DebDecimal. So again, I'm not going to go into this,

00:11:29.679 --> 00:11:38.359
but this just gives you an idea of these are the steps within the first major step of creating

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:48.119
the vector. And so it's broken down here. And I'll just give you this slide, which is a

00:11:48.119 --> 00:11:55.239
simplified version of the creation of the class. This doesn't have any checks or anything, but you

00:11:55.239 --> 00:12:04.119
can see here the different arguments that we have on the left, the different vectors that can be

00:12:04.119 --> 00:12:10.479
put in for pounds, shillings, and pence. And then on the right, just the single one, and then the

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:21.000
attributes of each class. And then here we have the actual creation. And so with the DebLSD,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:27.880
when we want to keep these tripartite structures, I'm going to use a record style vector. And so

00:12:27.919 --> 00:12:41.400
this is essentially a list that has vectors of equal length. And so that gives us a basis from

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:49.799
which we can have this different structure, this tripartite structure. On the right,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:59.440
it's just essentially, again, a double vector. So here we have now, I'm skipping some steps,

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:07.880
right? But this is what it looks like if we implement our class. And so we can start here

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:14.520
on the left. We have now a function where we can create a class. And so we have different things

00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:19.760
that we can add into the pounds values, the shillings values, the pence values. And here,

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:32.799
we're going to take our standard basis of 12 and 20. And on the right is an equivalent vector that

00:13:32.799 --> 00:13:40.960
is decimalized. And here we have the printing methods that I've chosen. So again, these are

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:49.880
things that you can create. So here, I've chosen to include the base attributes and the unit

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:58.880
attribute. So it's very clear. And both work natively with TIBL. The record style vectors

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:06.400
are not fully integrated, but they're getting there. So the last thing I want to talk about

00:14:06.599 --> 00:14:13.760
here that I have time to talk about is the issue of casting and coercion, which is really at the

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:22.640
heart of what is happening as you are creating your vectors, your classes, and want them to

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:31.640
interact with other different classes. So the workflow is fairly simple. You have a boiler

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:36.320
plate that you're going to use on each time. And this is the same for casting and coercion,

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:41.599
where you define the method for the class, and then you give a default. Then you do the methods

00:14:41.599 --> 00:14:47.799
within the class, and then the methods with any compatible classes that you decide to choose.

00:14:47.799 --> 00:14:57.280
So what coercion and casting do is they are kind of two sides of the same coin. Coercion

00:14:57.919 --> 00:15:08.039
looks for and determines what the common type is with this function, VecpType2, while casting

00:15:08.039 --> 00:15:16.239
does the actual transformation. And so things like comparison between classes are made possible by

00:15:16.239 --> 00:15:23.599
implementing both of these things. So again, I don't have a chance to go through all this,

00:15:23.679 --> 00:15:31.320
but coercion is really about design choices. There's not necessarily that much code that

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:36.880
goes into something like this. And so in this instance with debVectors, I decided to have a

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:46.239
double goes to a debDecimal, which would then go to a debLSD. So if you had these three types in

00:15:47.080 --> 00:15:57.640
a combined function, then you would get a debLSD. Casting is a little bit more interesting,

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:05.159
because this is where we have the programmatic logic of the actual transformation. And one reason

00:16:05.159 --> 00:16:12.559
why I think that debVectors is an interesting example of this is because I have two different

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:18.599
kinds of vectors, and so you have to think about how you can combine them in different ways. And

00:16:18.599 --> 00:16:28.080
so here, again, the code is not necessarily super easy to read, but this is taking a debDecimal and

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:35.599
then converting it to this tripartite structure. And essentially what I'm doing is taking simple

00:16:35.719 --> 00:16:46.400
if-else statement, what is the unit, and then from that unit, placing it where it should be in a

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:54.640
call to create a debLSD vector, and then finally normalizing it so that we get a normalized value,

00:16:54.640 --> 00:17:03.159
so that we've done the compound unit arithmetic. Okay, so how do we put it all together? So this

00:17:03.359 --> 00:17:09.319
is essentially the endpoint. Here I'm just showing what you can get. So we can combine debLSD,

00:17:09.319 --> 00:17:19.959
debDecimal, and double, and we get debLSD. We can compare different types, so 3,255 pence is less

00:17:19.959 --> 00:17:28.959
than 15 pounds. And again, if you go on, you can do arithmetic, including arithmetic with different

00:17:29.239 --> 00:17:37.760
types. So what I want to say is that you can create your own S3 vectors. You can extend the

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:45.520
capabilities of R to fit your own needs, and that vectors provides this clear developmental path

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:48.520
that enables you to do this. Thank you.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:18:02.199
Thank you very much, Jesse. That was fantastic. We have a couple of questions. If you still want

00:18:02.199 --> 00:18:07.439
to sneak one in, please do. There's a question about whether you can comment on your choice

00:18:07.439 --> 00:18:15.239
between, you mentioned explicitly S3 and vectors. Did you consider R6 classes, and how did that

00:18:15.239 --> 00:18:24.359
factor into your decision making? So I looked at it a little bit, but mostly I was sort of

00:18:24.359 --> 00:18:31.160
interested in the simplicity of S3. And like I said, I basically wrote the entire package with

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:40.959
S3 based on lists, and then I talked to Hadley, and then I had like a month of work to do. So the

00:18:40.959 --> 00:18:47.800
second question is, once you had your data in vectors format, what did you have to do

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:59.560
additionally to make it compatible with Tidyverse? So like I said, especially if your vector is based

